  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theory—it's a real, visible problem that affects people like me, who grew up in a diverse neighborhood in Milan. I've seen how students from immigrant families, especially those with parents who didn't finish school, often feel pressure to prove themselves in science classes because of stereotypes about their abilities. As someone with a bachelor's degree in a field unrelated to STEM, I know that these fears can be deeply personal. When a student believes they're 'not good enough' because of their background, their performance drops—not because they're less capable, but because the stress of being judged by others' expectations takes a toll. It's a cycle that's hard to break, especially in a system that often assumes certain groups are less inclined toward technical fields. I think we absolutely need to address this. In my work as a hairdresser, I've learned that communication and empathy are key—so in education, we should focus on creating safe spaces where students feel they can express their doubts without fear of judgment. Schools should integrate workshops that normalize the idea that everyone has the potential to excel in STEM, not just those who fit a specific mold. It's not about changing the curriculum but about changing the culture. For example, having teachers model curiosity and humility in their own learning can help students see that making mistakes is part of the process. The solution isn't a one-size-fits-all approach; it's about listening to the students and adapting to their needs. As an immigrant myself, I've seen how stereotypes can make people feel isolated, so addressing stereotype threat means building bridges, not walls.",
